    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense, but it sounds pretty one-sided. It feels like there's a lot of room for them to claim I did something wrong just to trigger those costs. Are there any specific \"red flags\" or sneaky ways this wording could be used against a freelancer in a way that isn't immediately obvious?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You are right to be wary; this clause is written heavily in favor of the Disclosing Party. A sneaky use of this language could be the very broad phrase \"arising out of or resulting from,\" which is a classic legal trap. It can be interpreted so widely that *any* minor issue related to the confidential information could be spun into a \"breach,\" forcing you to cover their legal fees. It's not always a clear-cut case of you intentionally leaking the data; sometimes, it's just a gray area they can exploit. You might want to negotiate a carve-out that limits liability to actual, demonstrable breaches, not just \"resulting from\" vague circumstances.",
      "source": "target",
